<h1>Overview</h1>
<hr>
<p>Cash flow strategies are about how a portfolio is constructed to handle cash inflow (income stream) and cash outflow (spending or withdrawing). When cash is deposited into a portfolio, when and how much is allocated to an asset class could have material impact on the portfolio's return. Similarly, when and how much an asset is sold to accommodate cash withdrawal not only could have impact on the portfolio return but also on the life of the portfolio value.</p>

<p>ValidFi collects two cash investment strategies: Value Averaging and Dollar Cost Average (DCA). These strategies are closely related to other strategies such as portfolio rebalancing strategies.</p>

<p>For a retirement account, there have been numerous studies on withdrawal rate. ValidFi collects some of the strategies and plans to offer many more as time goes.</p>

<p>Other strategies include target date funds or life cycle funds.</p>

<p>Typical measures for cash flow strategies are the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) and residual portfolio values after a period of time. </p>

